\int t \sqrt{1+t}\,dt
u = t
du = dt
\int u\,\frac{dv}{dt}dt = uv - \int v\,\frac{du}{dt}dt
dv = \sqrt{1+t} \;dt = (1+t)^{1/2} \;dt\implies v = \dfrac 23 (1+ t)^{3/2}
\begin{align}\int t\,\sqrt{1+t}\;dt & = \frac 23 t\,(1+t)^{3/2} - \frac 23 \int (1+t)^{3/2}\, dt\\ \\ & = \frac 23 t\,(1+t)^{3/2} - \frac 4{15}(1+t)^{5/2} + C\end{align}
\int \underbrace{t}_{=u}\underbrace{\sqrt{1+t}}_{=v'}dt=\frac{2}3t(1+t)^{3/2}-\frac23\int(1+t)^{3/2}dt=\frac{2}3t(1+t)^{3/2}-\frac4{15}(1+t)^{5/2}+C
I =\int t\cdot \left( 1+t\right) ^{1/2}dt=t\cdot \frac{2}{3}\left( 1+t\right) ^{3/2}-\int 1\cdot\frac{2}{3} \left( 1+t\right) ^{3/2}\,dt. 
u^2=1+t
dt=2udu
t=u^2-1
